[normal]Written evidence submitted [bold]by [bold]Professor [bold]Andrew Le [bold]Sueur[bold], Professor of Constitutional Justice, University of Essex (CRJ 0[bold]9[bold])[bold]Introduction[bold]What is the constitutional role of the judiciary and in what principal respects would the role of change if the United Kingdom were to move towards a codified constitution?[bold]What forms of consultation with the judiciary would be necessary to ensure that the legal and judicial implications of codifying the constitution were taken into account?[bold]If the UK were to have a codified constitution, what powers should the courts have if they held that a piece of legislation was unconstitutional? [bold]If there were a codified constitution, should the courts be able to assess the constitutional validity of a Bill before it becomes an Act? What would be the advantages and disadvantages of such a system?[bold]Would a Constitutional Court function best as part of the Supreme Court, or should it be separate? If the latter, how should it be appointed?[bold]18 November 2013
